454-553. Evander and Aeneas in the morning confer together. Evander advises Aeneas to seek the aid of the Etruriam, who have thrown off the authority of the wicked King Mezentius 3 placing under his command at the same time all the forces he himself can raise, and with them his son Pallas. While they are engaged in this conference the clang of gleaming armor and the sound of a trumpet are heard in the sky. Aeneas sends back a part of his followers to Ascanius with tidings of his success, while with the rest he prepares to depart into Etruria.

454. Lemnium Vulcan, according to mythology, was cast from heaven, and fell upon the island of Lemnos, where he was nurtured, and after-ward worshiped as the tutelary deity of the island. ’

456. volucrum: roos-swallows are meant.

457. inducitur artus: ‘ clothes his limbs '3 middle use. See note on 11, 275.

458. Tyrrhena: ‘Tuscan'; i.e. primitive.

461. limine ab alto: to be understood literally. The threshold was corn- monly of stone, and elevated' from the ground.

461, 462. gemini custodes canes: ‘ two dogs, guardians (of the house).’

463. secreta: ‘ retirement! 468. licito: now at length the important conference was ‘permitted ’ by

the circumstances, — both leisure and privacy.

472. pro nomine tanto: for such reputation as is ascribed to me, the aid 1 can afford is small.

473. Tusco: the Tiber is frequently called Tuscan, because it rises in Etru- ria and flows along its borders.

475. populoaz the Etrurians were divided into twelve nations or populi, each having its own king, or Iucunw, and when assembled for war one of the lucumones was appointed chief. Their camp, or army, thus composed, is ‘ rich in kingdoms ’3 i.e. made up of many royal armieS.

479. There was a tradition current among the Romans that the Etrurians came originally from Lydia in Asia Minor. See note on 11, 781.

481. deinde: ‘ then ’ or ‘ afterward ’3 join with tenuit.

489. infanda: adverbially with furentem.

493. The infinitives here are historical. defendier: cs. IV, 493.

497. puppes: i.e. = populi. They are assembled on the sea-shore, not sar from Caere, ready to sail for the coast of Latium, near Ardea.

499. Πεθοιιίαοε an older name for Lydia. See note on l. 479.

504. Hoc: Evander points across the Tiber in the direction of Caere, where the Etrurians are encamped. Their territory extends to the Tiber, opposite Evander 3 hence Hoc campo.

506. Tarchon: the lucum in temporary command of the Etrurians. Cf. note on l. 475.
